manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: Key Features Stainless Steel Soleplate Noted for its ability to smoothly glide across all fabric types, this soleplate material delivers high durability and resistance to scratching along with long-term satisfaction. Variable Steam and Temperature Controls Customize settings independently for versatility. The temperature control dial features recommended steam level settings for helpful guidance. Anti-Drip Engineered to prevent dripping by regulating water at the proper temperature to generate steam. 10-Foot Cord The generous 10-foot pivoting cord creates an easy reach, whether to an ironing board, or when vertically steaming drapes and curtains.

3-Way Auto Shutoff For peace of mind, the iron will power down if left inactive for 30 seconds on the soleplate or side, or after 8 minutes on its heel rest. The power light will blink to signal that the iron is going into shutoff mode. Simply move the iron to cancel the shutdown. Features Heavy-Duty Stainless Steel Soleplate Variable Steam and Temperature Controls 3-Way Auto-Shutoff Auto Clean System Anti-Drip Engineering

Auto Clean System Keep the iron in optimal condition for long-lasting performance with this integrated system featuring a built-in setting that flushes the iron of residue and water sediment. Comfort Grip Handle Ergonomically shaped handle with soft grip provides added comfort and minimizes fatigue. Vertical Steaming This iron can double as a handy steamer when used in an upright position for quick touch-ups right on the hanger, or for steaming curtains and drapes. Steam Surge Blast away tough wrinkles with the steam surge, which also works vertically for steaming curtains and clothes on the hanger. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 28, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Got to love a light iron
reviews.reviewText: Order this for my sister for Christmas at her request. Her daughter has one and she was having iron envy over it. It's light weight but has all the things a good iron needs. Steam and a lot of different temp settings to take it easy. She sews a lot and a good iron can be critical to making clothes that fit right.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on March 28, 2015
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars 11 years out of the 1st one, 7 years out of #2!
reviews.reviewText: Update: 12/27/21Well... it finally needs to be replaced. The steam function is in some kind of overdrive and can't be turned off and I'm sure it will start leaking soon. If I didn't need the steam function, I guarantee this will still work. I'm upgrading back to 5 stars because I paid under $25 bucks and it lasted 7 years. That's not bad! Already ordered the exact same iron before updating this review. 3 photos are after 7 years of use.Update: 8/5/2018The rarely used spray button popped off. Looking at the button, it seems defective when made. One side of the plastic clamp is thin and flimsy and not symmetrical. It cracked while attached to the iron from the inside and would have given out over time. I found it on the floor and hadn't even noticed it missing on the iron. Now a big hole. It would be nice if B&D sent me a replacement spray button to snap in. Downgrading from 5 to 3 stars.Update: 8/17/2016This thing still works great over a year and a half later. I use distilled or bottled water in it, very rarely do I use tap water in any iron that I own. I iron the area/garment I need to iron and place the iron in a resting upright position, and I don't use any ironing accessories or gadgets other than the ironing board. I have used Proctor, Rowenta, Sunbeam, and Shark irons. B&D is the best in my opinion which lasts forever and takes a beating. NEVER BUY A NON-STICK IRON... ever ever ever ever! Stainless steel is the way to go, and I wouldn't purchase an iron with any type of digital anything or excessive controls.Original Review:Purchased Jan 26th, 2015 - Had it for 2 months so far and Zero Problems. My last B&D Iron I purchased from Walmart in 2005 lasted 10 years! (it did take a couple of exchanges to get a good one). At year 8, it started leaking occasionally while ironing, but I learned not to leave the iron down too long... and it lasted another two years before the leaking got out of control. Honestly, I wanted to see how long it would last, and wanted to use it until it broke, but I couldn't it take it anymore. I would iron Officer Uniforms 5 days a week non-stop for at least 300 days a year, and I use the Steam button heavily. When the Iron is not on a garment, it is in the upright position.I considered other brands, even consumer reports recommendations. This one was not recommended and I bet it will do just fine.
